05420nam a22008055i 9780231530606DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019981142  a97802315306067 a10.7312/azma195362doi  a(DE-B1597)544646  a(OCoLC)1107150951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHB501 4aHB501b.A96 2020 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a330.12/2223  aLB 450002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90560:7721 aAzmanova, Albena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCapitalism on Edge :bHow Fighting Precarity Can Achieve Radical Change Without Crisis or Utopia /cAlbena Azmanova. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory ;v6900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: “How Come?” Asked the Befuddled Left -- t1. The Crisis of Capitalism, Almost -- t2. Capitalism Under Scrutiny: From Concept to Critique -- t3. Ideologies for the New Century -- t4. The Life and Times of Democratic Capitalism -- t5. Precarity Capitalism -- t6. What Is Ailing the 99 Percent? -- t7. Getting Unstuck: Overcoming Capitalism Without Crisis, Revolution, or Utopia -- tConclusion: The Radical Pragmatism of Bidding Capitalism Farewell -- tAppendix: Summary of Theoretical Framework -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe wake of the financial crisis has inspired hopes for dramatic change and stirred visions of capitalism’s terminal collapse. Yet capitalism is not on its deathbed, utopia is not in our future, and revolution is not in the cards. In Capitalism on Edge, Albena Azmanova demonstrates that radical progressive change is still attainable, but it must come from an unexpected direction.Azmanova’s new critique of capitalism focuses on the competitive pursuit of profit rather than on forms of ownership and patterns of wealth distribution. She contends that neoliberal capitalism has mutated into a new form—precarity capitalism—marked by the emergence of a precarious multitude. Widespread economic insecurity ails the 99 percent across differences in income, education, and professional occupation; it is the underlying cause of such diverse hardships as work-related stress and chronic unemployment. In response, Azmanova calls for forging a broad alliance of strange bedfellows whose discontent would challenge not only capitalism’s unfair outcomes but also the drive for profit at its core. To achieve this synthesis, progressive forces need to go beyond the old ideological certitudes of, on the left, fighting inequality and, on the right, increasing competition. Azmanova details reforms that would enable a dramatic transformation of the current system without a revolutionary break. An iconoclastic critique of left orthodoxy, Capitalism on Edge confronts the intellectual and political impasses of our time to discern a new path of emancipation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCapitalism. 0aEquality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2019z978311066221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/azm